Victory of the populist right in Austria, together they form 29 %
Early elections to the Austrian parliament have brought, according to the early results, a noticeable weakening of both parties of the current grand coalition and an expressive strengthening of the populist right-wing party.
Strong and special losses have been suffered by the Austrian People's Party (OVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously reeling.
On the contrary, the leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZO), the head of the government of the state of Carinthia, J.rg Haider, is preparing his triumphant return to national politics.
According to the approximate results, social democracy (SP) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, so it loses 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last elections in 2006.
Worse is the OVP, which loses 25.6 percent, almost nine percent of the vote, is still over.
They are the worst results, literally catastrophic, in the history of these two major Austrian parties since the post-war period and especially for the popular who called these early elections.
Even in early July, when the OVP left the coalition, the popular had preference to the SPO, a considerable advantage.
It is clear, however, that voters punished them for letting the government shipwreck.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculations about the resignation of the party president and, until today, vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer were heard.
Observers believe that this could be achieved as early as Monday at the exceptional meeting of the party presidency.
Such an evolution would obviously facilitate the path of the constant and more approximate starting point of the election results, that is, the renewal of the grand coalition between SPO and OVP.
In view of the fact that the reinforcement of both parties on the populist right - the Liberals (FPOs) have won about 18 percent and the BZO, eleven percent of the vote - and that the Social Democrats at the same time expressed their fears that the same would be repeated in 1999 when the popular negotiated with the populists (then FPO was a unit, but in 2005 it dismembered from BZO) for a coalition government that led to a sanction by the European Union.
Haider has clearly bet on this evolution who has already announced that he is prepared to collaborate with any party and that he is already assuming his return to Vienna, to national politics.
The Green Party has also managed to reach parliament although it has lost slightly and dropped from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party clearly exceeded the four per cent limit and therefore is not part of parliament.
