The first virtual operator is already going to arrive, this year, in the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is well developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not gonna be long.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech T-Smart Office, which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to be reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible for prices in the Czech Republic to remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there's no competition I really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to lament that there is extreme competition on the Czech market.
This is also the Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (T'), Pavel Dvoák, and said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile telephony market brought a significant price drop to which the classic operators should also react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for these types of operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, there is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group that, apart from this, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is in the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they are enough with far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large costs in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that, however, are often offset by the supply of tighter services.
For example, mobile Tesco in Britain offers SMS at least half of the cheap ones in terms of competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it may also be a good blow to the bet also on a no trivial target group.
This operator specifically addresses the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it's the operator he likes and who you can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which works for this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether the concept like that of Poland could hook in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Eepick is in doubt: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition from the point of view of the offer of services it is relatively saturated"
There is no possibility in the Czech Republic, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operator in the Czech Republic that it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the R. He doesn't seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," Jana Studnieková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone conversation for mobil.cz.
Indirectly, he assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not bowing to this idea.
Rather the opposite, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competition emerges.
Interest on the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, so that we can offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile phone services.
And how much sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to move forward with the meetings," said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
So maybe they're flashing better times.
It seems that, due to unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this area," said Vlastimil Sr.e, spokesman for Telefónica O2.
Other operators are concerned about the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional agreement with O2's opinion, adds: "Until today we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop."
He adds: "On the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find any virtual operator until the end of the year.
At the moment we should already have on the table some specific contract that could be studied on such a short horizon."
Vodafone is focusing instead on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Eepick adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost- and infrastructure sharing.
Precisely we consider it the biggest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a price drop and thus a decline in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same string, proof of which is the grip when U:fon came up.
Perhaps the greatest pressure to the T was at the time of U:fon's entry by the T-Mobile society.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the websites of the T.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened to a fourth operator.
As far as the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would be for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the YOU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Licitations (OHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile phone operator and a virtual operator is concluded.
To this day no agreement has been closed since the offer of the potential stakeholders rather was not interesting enough for the classic operators," Kristián Chalupa of the external relations department of the OHS added to our question.
These statements are not surprising to the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from that they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "At the outside where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the drop in prices of mobile phone services."
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market means and the price drop does not fall within the interest of the OHS.
The dramatically shocking thing in this whole case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it's really a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a tough fight for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore does not have reasons for any intervention.
None of the operators have a dominant position therefore do not have a corresponding ascent of responsibility in their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators are rather lacking, as well as telecommunications regulators," Chalupa added to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is obviously a relevant market analysis prepared by the T-T that telecoms are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market naturally none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
But some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge, an agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for OHS should be a warning that three mobile operators are strikingly ascending in a similar way.
The current complaints of the interested parties (inlusioned by the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they clash with many similar impediments.
Loading responsibility for the T is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the OHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We've met him in some similar cases already.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently tabled for the extension of the competence of the T in the field of commercial tenders that was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be perfectly known to the representatives of O.S, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything's fine, when nobody looks
At the same time, something like a pseudovirtual operator that on Czech mobile phone networks already exist a few are unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only one party are public.
These are usually companies that engage in multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally only a few of them get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with regard to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the company by commissioning a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be heard as infringement under contract terms that could result in an end to collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová replied to the question on this issue.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned, they may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make uns negligible profits and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Eepick warns us of the possible problems: "the law allows speculation of this type, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percent of customers.
They must also accept that their phone's SIM card is not in their name so they can't absolutely dispose of it as a normal operator customer.'
Precisely this is what it should look like to the minimally weird.
Also a new question for the OHS appears.
If mobile phone operators engulf the eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the virtual operator's entry?
It should be added that the LOS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if you are not going to want you should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the virtual operator's entry into the mobile telephony market led to a significant decrease in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried to protect themselves from this break-in.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulators have now intervened and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, they got the first virtual operator to emerge and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory body this whole case is happening as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let's not waste.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really gets to this land, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators let any virtual mobile operator in, it will be difficult for the OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And maybe we'll stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
