The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention Nissan has been inspired, this time, in nature, in particular bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the Security Shield from four areas of Nissan.
This robot intends to strengthen the collision prevention capacity of branded vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates their own personal oval-shaped space that looks a lot like Nissan's Shield of Safety.
But the most important thing is the composite eyes of the bee, able to see with an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within your own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles that are up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius in front of BR23C, calculates the distance to that object and sends a signal to a onboard microprocessor that immediately translates into the prevention of the collision.
"At the time you detect an obstacle, the small robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at right or greater angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate up or down, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to rotate its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act according to that data.
It does not require saving information or intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can work continuously with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may be surprising, but we're not talking about gigas of memory, not even megas."
This is the first step to developing new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced into serial cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the lithium-ion variety.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination by avoiding obstacles along the way.
