Talk asleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean these who wake up very savvy by telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk asleep.
The first time it happens maybe you get a scare, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign sleep disturbance called somnochios.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with a high fever episode), or more regularly (every day, once a week, once in meseS...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause to determine its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (footed asleep) or sleeping sleep, but it doesn't have to be so.
As we have mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitence.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the demonstration is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issues that are generating a lot of anxiety and gives him way out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disturbance that can be treated (e.g. if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to get the child too excited before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid TV shows or series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who find it very difficult to relax, relaxing techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain internal calm.
This will encourage the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the sleepy ones appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day you won't remember anything that has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not conscious, and you'll break his dream.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and is therefore resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes you should consult or find out what generates so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what you say (which is not the most common), do not fall into the temptation to ask you an interrogation to please you to extract information.
You will get nothing, because when you are asleep you are not conscious enough to organize your thought.
Besides, you'll hear what he says, but you don't know what he's dreaming of to say that, so he's very careful how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
I'm not even kidding.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's not bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
