Morgan Stanley announced the entry into its capital of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG), the first Japanese bank, which will disburse nine billion dollars to acquire 21 per cent of its capital, a news that has been accepted with a sharp drop in its stock exchange listing.
A week after unveiling an interim deal, both banks explained that MUFG would buy 9.9 percent of Morgan Stanley ordinary shares at the per unit price of $25.25, or $3 billion.
The agreed price is less than 19 per cent of the book value of the securities as at 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional $6 billion with the purchase of convertible securities which will ensure a return of 10 per cent and a conversion price of $31.25.
Morgan Stanley specified that the global transaction would be carried out on the basis of a unit price of 29 dollars, or 28 per cent above its current change.
Morgan Stanley shares lost 6.79 per cent to $23.07 each at 17:00 GMT.
"This strategic partnership is an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley's transition to bank holding status," explained Juan Mack, the CEO of the American group.
Morgan Stanley adopted the new statute last week, which would have to allow him to diversify his activities but he moves on under the authority of the Federal Reserve.
His alliance with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces Wall Street's biggest names to adopt much more cautious behavior than before.
The modalities presented last Monday also show that the agreement has been modified over the past few days: last Monday, Morgan had announced that it would sell up to 20 percent of its shares to Japanese for almost $8.5 billion.
"A week ago," Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG's chief executive, explained in Tokyo, "we thought the stake would have been made up only of ordinary shares.
But in view of the current situation of the economy and the market, we have wanted to minimize the risks and cover ourselves. "
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay its Morgan Stanley securities 7 % below its book value.
And the operation will result in a dilution of about 20 percent of the profit per share.
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares within a year if they are sold at more than 50 per cent above the conversion price, or $47 or so, for a given period.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital provided by MUFG will allow it to take investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
