The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday its 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again been one of the safest and most effective suppliers of blood in the world.
And above all, it regained the public's confidence that it had seriously been hesitated by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and make recommendations so that such a disaster should not be reproduced anymore.
While Judge Krever was slow to present their relationship, some provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee accomplished this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two providers have been created in Canada: Hemema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38 percent of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," Decary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence," he says before proudly stating that in early 2008, about 94 per cent of the Quebec population was now confident in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "confidence is something extremely fragile."
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Decary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, we set up exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied had the meaning. "
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV detection appeared on the market: nuclei acid tests that allow the presence of the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The nuclei acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements allowed the risk of contracting AIDS considerably lowered by a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
'That means 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before an HIV transmission case is overtaken by a blood product.
I think you can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain health without worries," says the head of the management of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen might emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by a blood insect.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary pursues before stressing that in addition to a secure supply, Hema-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing because the population ages.
Because the most aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has consequences for the network of blood donors, which annually brings together on average only 3 per cent of eligible Quebeckers to blood donation. "
All people in good health, aged 18 and corresponding to the eligibility criteria, however, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who propose their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3 %, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But members of this network of donors must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it's hard to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to hold them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since today's life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood," Francine Décary grieves.
With a budget of $297 million a year, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with rich blood of stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bench of our thousandth blood sample of the umbilical cord and is expected to get more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts early next year," says Doctor Decary who describes this lace-blood-wielding program as very popular.
"Many moms are disappointed not to be able to enjoy this," as Hema-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
