Psychology of the overlapping: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are prone to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at New York University discovered the neurological - economical bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study in the journal Science, people don't want to lose out in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment were examined through the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI).
In both games participants could make money, but during auctions, where it is essential to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called a stratum under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-advancement" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To substantiate their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet on a person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the real value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group, in addition, was promised that if they win, they would receive $15 more prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of losing the auction the group's members even lost that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the neurologists' hypothesis, members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any economic theory previously existing.
For those until now explained the phenomena of the auctions only with the joy of winning and the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor at New York University's faculty of economics.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
World around 500 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease in Hungary is considered one of the main causes of death.
It is estimated at one hundred thousand the number of people infected in this country, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are a lot of similar; liver and jaundice infection are characteristic, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses in dependence on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (waiting, vagina mood, saliva).
Travelers are recommended to protect themselves by vaccine against the A and B viruses, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating the infected food, manifested through a general poor condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that the jaundice appears on the skin and white of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, the urine dark and the healing can last even two - three weeks.
Annually one million people die in the world in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to calculations, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can lead to liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that he is sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature examination, systematic medical control, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those wearing tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory check-up as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has cure if discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so contagion can be suppressed and cancer prevented.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its objective is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
