According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Oxford University scientists conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in what way it influences human pain, the British newspaper Telegraph reported.
As part of this unique experiment, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists applied electric shock, meanwhile everyone was watching a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of research in which, alongside academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate.
The analysis occurred as follows; they fixed a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the work of 17th century Sassoferrato and Leonardo da Vinci's Lady of the 15th century.
The researchers had hoped that the show of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during the period while watching the religious-themed paint or the other.
Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and in their hearts peace reigned."
Looking at the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any such shocking image you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you only have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively about, like a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases really changes our personality," Wright added.
After these formidable results there is only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if Leonardo's Madonna or another painter of his size were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
