The smart car mimics the bee flight
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not imitation of existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the bumblebee.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebee gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C automotive robotic steering system of nature imitator, which was given the characteristics of the buzzers, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bubble creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role the composite eyes of the bumblebees who are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, engineers used the laser-length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any current system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough to dodge obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It should react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are now considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike the bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonal, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of spin of the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotating movement and acceleration also the brake.
The BR23C uses litho-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is higher, meaning they have a longer life lifespan than that of lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, let alone the storage capacity.
This device in each second should only process some input signals and react as appropriate.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No memory of gigabytes, or megabytes, are needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately dodge the obstacles, which according to Nissan's calculations, in ten years' time it will be able to join the models manufactured in series.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, dodging the obstacles in his path.
