On the bill called the 2008 economic stabilization emergency bill, the first Monday will be voted by the American Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress made overnight and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
The program is different from the Bush administration's original proposal to spend all of the $700 billion to buy securities of poor quality credit fund.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, the Finance Ministry will buy credit, poorly rated securities of credit and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This program will be controlled by a special agency, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion could be spent after a new congressional decision.
Under the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it will be able to simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and credit fund securities, in addition to other "poisonous" loans as well.
The purchase can be made at auctions or directly - competent persons of the ministry reported.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
