Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent from July 2008 and fell 3.9 per cent from the previous year.
And as a result of domestic and export price changes, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent from the previous month and 3.2 per cent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose by just one measure, at 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors rose minimally, up 0.1 percent from July.
The largest increase in the size of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), due in the first place to increase the bags and belts per month and the 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the timber processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper manufacturing, publishers and printing presses did not change.
The other sectors of the processing industry saw a price increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent in August was an increase of 0.3 per cent, first of all as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a 12-month comparison - in domestic sales of processing industry sectors - the biggest price increase was in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, which was decisive, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the pace of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally, prices rose 10.2 per cent.
Electricity prices, gas, heat and water supplies exceeded prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in the prices of the energy sector and the intermediary sectors, there was no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month last year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer product branches there was a decrease of 6.8 per cent and investment goods by 1.4 per cent.
Industry export prices calculated at HUF were up 1.1 percent from the previous month, and compared with 12 months, there was a 3.9 percent decline.
The price of our national currency in a month fell by 1.7 percent against the euro and 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened with 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
